<TITLE> Stocks ride on retail investors </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sep 7 (bdnews24.com)  Stocks gained on the opening day of the week on perked-up trading, which led buying almost equal to selling. Retail investors were back on trading after a break due to instability in the market, according to brokerage house officials. "It seems that small-scale investors are back to make some money ahead of the Eid," an official of IDLC securities told bdnews24.com, who declined to be named. The blue chip shares on the twin bourses, however, continued to fall. Dhaka Stock Exchange's benchmark DGEN or general index ended 21.06 points, or 0.75 percent higher on 2824.03. The DSI or all-share price index finished at 2404.15, edging up 6.40 points or 0.26 percent. The blue-chip DSE-20 shed 1.61 points, or 0.06 percent, to close at 2407.38. Indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange followed the prime bourse; edging up except the blue chips. The CSCX or selective categories index crept up 7.64 points, or 0.13 percent, to close on 5657.61. The CASPI or all-share price index closed at 8665.64, advancing 9.73 points or 0.11 percent. The bourse's blue-chip CSE-30 slumped 62.62 points, or 0.80 percent, on 7686.26. Increased investors' participation caused the trading volume and turnover to rise substantially from last week's closing day. Turnover on the DSE was Tk 3.04 billionwith 18,989,400 shares changing handsup from Tk 2.36 billion on Thursday. Turnover on the port city's bourse surged to Tk 377.99 million from previous trading day's Tk 293.45 million, with 3,482,280 traded shares. Losers beat gainers on the DSE by 106 to 103, while 10 issues held steady. On the CSE, 60 issues lost, 63 gained, and six remained unchanged. Titas Gas continued to top the turnover board, closing at Tk 468.50, up by 2.96 percent. ACI was the second in line, rising 3.58 percent to Tk 537.30. Beximco surged 10.71 percent from the previous day to finish at Tk 135.40. ICB AMCI 2nd NRB Mutual Fund ended on Tk 199, gaining 11.48 percent. Grameen One: Scheme 2 continued to advance closing at Tk 43.20, up by 7.19 percent. The other scrips on the turnover board, S Alam Cold Rolled Steels, Beximco Pharmaceuticals, Lanka Bangla Finance, Pragati Insurance and AB Bank rose on buying pressure. bd
